==English==

===Etymology===
Old English ''[[pund]]''

===Pronunciation===
*Rhymes: [[Rhymes:English:-aʊnd|-aʊnd]]

====Noun====
{{en-noun}}

#A [[unit]] of [[mass]], depending on the system used consisting of either 16 or 12 corresponding [[ounce]]s (approximately 454 or 373 [[gram]]s respectively).
# [[pound-force|Pound-force.]]
# A unit of [[currency]] used in Cyprus; Egypt; Lebanon; the United Kingdom and its [[dependency|dependencies]]; and formerly in the Republic of Ireland (which now uses the [[euro]]). Its symbol is <big>'''&pound;'''</big>

===Etymology===
Middle English
====Noun====
{{en-noun}}

# A place for the detention of stray or wandering [[animal]]s.
# A place for the detention of automobiles that have been illegally parked, abandoned, etc.
# A hard blow.
# (''US'') The symbol '''#''' <!--isn't this "pound sign" rather than "pound"?-->
'''Usage note:''' [[w:Manx English|Manx English]] uses this word uncountably.

